MidiMonitor2
(c)2026 David Beckman

I have adapted Bill Thibault's Midi Monitor 1.0 app, originally released for 
BeOS r4's MidiKit, to instead use the MidiKit2 of Haiku OS and BeOS r5.
While I was debugging my latest Haiku app, I found myself in need of one my
favorite MIDI tools for the BeOS, Midi Monitor.  The original binary and code 
was having issues running under Haiku_x86, so I fixed it, converted it to a 
MidiKit2 app, and did a little bit of other code cleanup.

From Bill's original description:
  MidiMonitor displays incoming MIDI messages.
  The user can select which physical MIDI input port to monitor.


  The color used to display a message is based on the
  "age" of the message: new messages in bright green,
  old messages in black. As messages age the color 
  fades to black: often just seeing the flash of
  an arriving message (from across the room, for example)
  is enough information to make the user happy.

  The window is fully resizable (based on William Adams' original
  Calendar example).  

  The code is not especially efficient, but will handle the
  densest MIDI streams without being swamped. The incoming
  MIDI stream is sampled at the "Pulse" rate (20 Hz).
  Only the most recent message is displayed.

R4 BeIDE projects for both PPC and Intel are still included.  
I know the original binaries worked in BeOS r5, but not sure 
if the project files will help with compiling for r5.  I will
find out soon, and update if necessary.
